1
00:00:05,492 --> 00:00:07,986
Welcome to the course
on Plasma Physics and Applications.

2
00:00:08,308 --> 00:00:10,837
Today we will discuss
the heating of the plasma

3
00:00:10,837 --> 00:00:12,246
to thermonuclear temperatures,

4
00:00:12,246 --> 00:00:15,275
that is temperatures that are needed
for a fusion reactor to work.

5
00:00:16,096 --> 00:00:18,637
We will start by discussing Ohmic heating,

6
00:00:18,637 --> 00:00:21,954
that is the heating of the plasma
by an electrical current,

7
00:00:22,318 --> 00:00:24,590
and the limitations of that method.

8
00:00:24,839 --> 00:00:28,607
Therefore we will illustrate
the need for additional plasma heating,

9
00:00:28,607 --> 00:00:32,713
additional meaning in addition to
the Ohmic heating method.

10
00:00:33,323 --> 00:00:35,873
We will then focus
on the first of the systems

11
00:00:35,873 --> 00:00:39,561
that they will consider for a reactor:
the neutral beam injection.

12
00:00:40,009 --> 00:00:43,315
We will explore
the processes that take place

13
00:00:43,315 --> 00:00:45,581
as the beam is injected into the plasma,

14
00:00:45,921 --> 00:00:49,499
the components that are needed
for the beam-injection system,

15
00:00:49,910 --> 00:00:55,433
the neutralization of the beam before
its injection to the tokamak plasma,

16
00:00:56,031 --> 00:00:58,674
and the requirements
that the beam needs to satisfy

17
00:00:58,674 --> 00:01:01,595
in order to be useable on large devices,

18
00:01:01,595 --> 00:01:04,174
for example on the ITER Tokamak.

19
00:01:04,850 --> 00:01:08,709
We will illustrate the example
of the NBI system

20
00:01:09,104 --> 00:01:11,203
that is operational on JET,

21
00:01:11,762 --> 00:01:16,233
and we'll say a few words about the design
of the NBI system for ITER.

22
00:01:16,841 --> 00:01:19,815
Finally, we'll discuss
the advantages and disadvantages

23
00:01:19,815 --> 00:01:23,707
of the NBI heating method
for a reactor in the future.

24
00:01:24,368 --> 00:01:28,154
First I'd like to remind ourselves
that we need power

25
00:01:28,483 --> 00:01:31,227
to initiate the plasma discharge,

26
00:01:31,227 --> 00:01:34,676
that is to ionize the gas
that we inject into the tokamak.

27
00:01:36,028 --> 00:01:37,962
That's fairly intuitive.

28
00:01:37,962 --> 00:01:40,472
On the other hand, what may be
a little bit less intuitive,

29
00:01:40,472 --> 00:01:42,779
is that we also need a certain power level

30
00:01:42,779 --> 00:01:45,396
to overcome what's called
a <i>radiation barrier</i>.

31
00:01:45,742 --> 00:01:49,893
The radiation barrier comes about because
the emission from light impurities

32
00:01:49,893 --> 00:01:53,807
that are present in our gas,
and then in the plasma,

33
00:01:54,764 --> 00:02:00,391
has a maximum for temperatures
that are typically of a few tens of eV,

34
00:02:01,051 --> 00:02:03,467
typically below 100 eV.

35
00:02:03,767 --> 00:02:06,905
And if the power that we inject
into the tokamak

36
00:02:06,905 --> 00:02:09,119
is lower than a certain critical value

37
00:02:09,119 --> 00:02:12,431
that is associated
with this impurity emission,

38
00:02:12,753 --> 00:02:16,063
then the temperature will never
be able to exceed this value

39
00:02:16,703 --> 00:02:18,210
that corresponds to the maximum

40
00:02:18,210 --> 00:02:20,953
of the emission of the light
by impurities.

41
00:02:21,782 --> 00:02:26,848
Typically, for a midsize tokamak,
we have taken the example here

42
00:02:26,848 --> 00:02:30,121
of, say, a two-meter major radius tokamak,

43
00:02:30,121 --> 00:02:34,602
you need something like a megawatt
to fully ionize your gas,

44
00:02:34,602 --> 00:02:36,545
to make the plasma,

45
00:02:37,324 --> 00:02:42,590
and you need more than that,
something like 4-5 MW

46
00:02:42,590 --> 00:02:44,346
to overcome this radiation barrier.

47
00:02:44,346 --> 00:02:48,681
It's only after that level,
once the radiation barrier is overcome,

48
00:02:48,681 --> 00:02:52,589
that we manage to keep
increasing the temperature

49
00:02:52,589 --> 00:02:56,646
towards values that are
of interest for thermonuclear reactions,

50
00:02:57,086 --> 00:03:02,082
and the efficiency and therefore
the slope of the curve

51
00:03:02,752 --> 00:03:04,915
of the increase of temperature

52
00:03:04,915 --> 00:03:08,417
with the additional power
injected into the plasma

53
00:03:08,417 --> 00:03:13,502
of course depends on the levels
of transport the plasma has, and so on.

54
00:03:14,613 --> 00:03:17,527
As you remember,
the concept of tokamak is based

55
00:03:17,527 --> 00:03:22,173
not only on external fields
that are produced by coils,

56
00:03:22,887 --> 00:03:24,634
mainly in the toroidal direction,

57
00:03:24,634 --> 00:03:27,879
but also by transformer action,

58
00:03:28,559 --> 00:03:32,473
that is by swinging the flux

59
00:03:32,473 --> 00:03:37,194
produced by the primary coil
of the transformer,

60
00:03:37,651 --> 00:03:41,960
and therefore inducing
an electromotive force in the plasma ring

61
00:03:42,506 --> 00:03:47,017
which therefore provides a drive
for a current through the plasma.

62
00:03:47,589 --> 00:03:49,871
Now, as the resistivity,

63
00:03:49,871 --> 00:03:52,337
as we have learned
in the first part of this course,

64
00:03:52,723 --> 00:03:57,369
is proportional to T^(-3/2),

65
00:03:58,037 --> 00:04:02,532
the profile of the current
that will be driven into the plasma

66
00:04:02,532 --> 00:04:08,276
will be strictly related to the profile
of the temperature of the plasma itself.

67
00:04:09,471 --> 00:04:11,152
So that's the first observation,

68
00:04:11,152 --> 00:04:13,180
but the second observation
is even more important,

69
00:04:13,180 --> 00:04:16,080
and that is that the Ohmic power,
let's call it Pohmic,

70
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:18,571
that I can dissipate into the plasma,
and in this case

71
00:04:18,571 --> 00:04:22,514
I'd like to heat the plasma
by passing current through it.

72
00:04:22,914 --> 00:04:27,299
is obviously equal to the loop voltage

73
00:04:27,672 --> 00:04:31,086
that's generated
by this transformer action,

74
00:04:31,086 --> 00:04:34,382
times the current
that flows into the plasma, Ip.

75
00:04:34,947 --> 00:04:38,181
That's the resistance of the whole plasma,

76
00:04:38,807 --> 00:04:40,872
times the current, square,

77
00:04:40,872 --> 00:04:44,048
and that is proportional
to the resistivity [Î·]

78
00:04:44,458 --> 00:04:46,637
times the current density square,

79
00:04:46,637 --> 00:04:50,048
so we will have a direct dependence
on the resistivity,

80
00:04:50,048 --> 00:04:55,454
therefore it will have
a dependence upon T^(-3/2).

81
00:04:56,350 --> 00:05:01,697
So if on one hand this current is
efficient in producing the poloidal field

82
00:05:01,697 --> 00:05:05,189
and needs to complete
the magnetic field structure

83
00:05:05,189 --> 00:05:08,419
for trapping the plasma into the tokamak,

84
00:05:09,618 --> 00:05:16,461
this current is progressively more
and more inefficient at heating the plasma

85
00:05:16,461 --> 00:05:18,273
as we increase its temperature.

86
00:05:18,449 --> 00:05:22,798
We can therefore discuss why we need,

87
00:05:22,798 --> 00:05:24,989
specifically, additional plasma heating.

88
00:05:24,989 --> 00:05:27,760
I like to illustrate that
in a semi-quantitative way,

89
00:05:27,886 --> 00:05:31,410
in a plot in which I represent vertically

90
00:05:31,410 --> 00:05:36,312
the power corresponding to different
channels in the plasma, say in MW.

91
00:05:36,312 --> 00:05:38,840
Say we take a logarithmic scale,

92
00:05:38,840 --> 00:05:44,393
say 1, 10, 100 and 1,000 MW,

93
00:05:44,393 --> 00:05:48,683
and I represent that as
a function of the temperature,

94
00:05:48,683 --> 00:05:52,399
say in keV, of the plasma.

95
00:05:52,399 --> 00:05:54,980
So we have just learned
that the Ohmic heating

96
00:05:55,809 --> 00:06:01,148
will go down with the power
of temperature to the 3/2,

97
00:06:01,148 --> 00:06:04,412
so say it will take a curve of this kind.

98
00:06:07,700 --> 00:06:13,387
I can also represent the horizontal axis
with a logarithmic scale.

99
00:06:14,677 --> 00:06:20,834
This is 10 keV, and then say all the way
to the right we have 100 keV.

100
00:06:21,473 --> 00:06:27,450
So the Ohmic heating power
goes down to a very low level

101
00:06:27,716 --> 00:06:32,603
before the plasma can reach
the temperature of the order of 10keV.

102
00:06:33,102 --> 00:06:36,938
The example taken here,
semiquantitatively, is an example

103
00:06:36,938 --> 00:06:40,498
of a -say- 1 meter major radius tokamak.

104
00:06:42,141 --> 00:06:43,954
So this is the Ohmic power,

105
00:06:44,868 --> 00:06:48,477
going down with the power
of T, temperature.

106
00:06:49,094 --> 00:06:53,327
Now, in a reactor
we will count at some point

107
00:06:54,212 --> 00:06:59,061
on the power provided by the heating
due to the alpha particles

108
00:06:59,061 --> 00:07:02,692
that are issued
by fusion reactions themselves,

109
00:07:02,692 --> 00:07:06,203
and that will be coming about
when the plasma temperature

110
00:07:06,203 --> 00:07:10,790
will be larger than a few keV's
so say it will be something like that.

111
00:07:12,050 --> 00:07:14,910
So this is the alpha heating power.

112
00:07:14,910 --> 00:07:18,633
And if we had no losses
it would be no problem,

113
00:07:18,633 --> 00:07:20,997
because we would use the Ohmic power

114
00:07:20,997 --> 00:07:24,604
all the way to the point,
which would be around a few KeV,

115
00:07:24,604 --> 00:07:28,492
where the alpha particle
heating would take over.

116
00:07:28,492 --> 00:07:30,416
But, we of course do have losses.

117
00:07:30,952 --> 00:07:34,516
We have losses in the form of radiation,
like bremsstrahlung,

118
00:07:34,516 --> 00:07:41,757
but also losses in the form
of a convective and conduction transport

119
00:07:42,241 --> 00:07:46,542
of ion and electron heat,
in particular, of ion heat.

120
00:07:46,851 --> 00:07:53,936
So let's put even the lowest possible
loss power that we can have,

121
00:07:53,936 --> 00:07:56,456
that of bremsstrahlung,

122
00:07:56,456 --> 00:07:59,782
and in all the circumstances
we can think about in practice,

123
00:08:00,162 --> 00:08:05,368
this bremsstrahlung level will be higher

124
00:08:05,368 --> 00:08:08,644
than the level at which
the curve of Ohmic power

125
00:08:08,644 --> 00:08:10,735
crosses that of the alpha heating power.

126
00:08:13,097 --> 00:08:19,079
So even without invoking any transport
from conduction and convection,

127
00:08:19,079 --> 00:08:22,381
which we actually know would
dominate the bremsstrahlung,

128
00:08:22,381 --> 00:08:28,015
so I can even perhaps just trace it,

129
00:08:28,015 --> 00:08:29,510
something like that,

130
00:08:30,349 --> 00:08:32,301
just call it <i>heat transport</i>.

131
00:08:33,962 --> 00:08:37,222
Even if we reduce that to a minimum level,
below bremsstrahlung level,

132
00:08:37,222 --> 00:08:40,618
which would be, in practice,
very, very difficult to do,

133
00:08:40,618 --> 00:08:43,016
we will have a gap, here,

134
00:08:44,232 --> 00:08:45,493
that is a region

135
00:08:48,553 --> 00:08:50,536
where we will not be able

136
00:08:51,163 --> 00:08:53,322
to connect the Ohmic power
to the alpha heating power.

137
00:08:53,322 --> 00:08:56,135
In other words, we have
a shortfall of power in this region,

138
00:08:56,135 --> 00:08:59,869
which is in the region
of a few keV of temperature

139
00:09:01,297 --> 00:09:05,787
where we need to do something,
and do something means

140
00:09:07,751 --> 00:09:11,614
heating the plasma
by other means than Ohmic power.

141
00:09:11,614 --> 00:09:16,751
So this gap needs to be filled
by what we call <i>additional heating</i>.

142
00:09:17,271 --> 00:09:22,010
So let's briefly review what options
do we have for heating the plasma,

143
00:09:22,010 --> 00:09:25,587
in addition to passing
electric current through it,

144
00:09:25,960 --> 00:09:28,185
which is what we refer to
as <i>Ohmic heating</i>.

145
00:09:28,647 --> 00:09:31,936
We may heat the plasma
by injecting a beam,

146
00:09:32,392 --> 00:09:37,605
of very energetic neutral particles
that will become ions,

147
00:09:37,605 --> 00:09:39,991
once they are entering the plasma.

148
00:09:41,439 --> 00:09:45,204
And these particles will transfer
their energy and momentum

149
00:09:45,204 --> 00:09:49,174
by collisions to the plasma particles,
and therefore will heat the plasma,

150
00:09:49,174 --> 00:09:54,464
or we can inject waves into the plasma.

151
00:09:54,464 --> 00:09:56,911
We have seen,
in previous parts of this course

152
00:09:56,911 --> 00:10:01,077
that there are several possibilities
for waves to exist in plasma,

153
00:10:01,077 --> 00:10:02,656
at different frequency ranges.

154
00:10:02,656 --> 00:10:04,634
We can inject waves that resonate,

155
00:10:04,634 --> 00:10:07,207
for example the electron species,
that would be high frequency,

156
00:10:07,207 --> 00:10:09,823
or we can inject waves
that resonate with the ion species,

157
00:10:09,823 --> 00:10:11,374
that would be lower frequency.

158
00:10:11,374 --> 00:10:15,158
And in both cases, we can transfer
power from these waves,

159
00:10:15,756 --> 00:10:19,102
that we can inject
using transmission lines

160
00:10:19,102 --> 00:10:22,264
and antennas that are close to the plasma

161
00:10:22,264 --> 00:10:26,106
to the plasma, therefore heating it
to thermonuclear temperatures.

162
00:10:26,844 --> 00:10:31,225
Today, as we said, we will focus
on the first of these methods,

163
00:10:31,746 --> 00:10:34,021
that is the neutral beam heating.

164
00:10:35,647 --> 00:10:39,363
So the idea here is to inject, somehow,

165
00:10:39,363 --> 00:10:42,150
energetic ions into the plasma,

166
00:10:42,511 --> 00:10:45,521
that would give the energy
to colder plasma particles.

167
00:10:45,835 --> 00:10:48,098
By energetic ions, we mean ions
that don't belong

168
00:10:48,098 --> 00:10:49,948
to the thermal distribution
of the plasma itself,

169
00:10:49,948 --> 00:10:53,776
so there should be much more energetic

170
00:10:53,776 --> 00:10:56,676
than the energy corresponding
to the plasma temperature.

171
00:10:57,796 --> 00:11:01,440
But how can we inject a beam of ions

172
00:11:01,909 --> 00:11:04,250
into a very complicated magnetic field

173
00:11:04,250 --> 00:11:06,635
that we had actually prepared, and set up,

174
00:11:06,635 --> 00:11:09,088
in order to avoid the leaking of plasma

175
00:11:09,088 --> 00:11:11,351
out from our confinement volume.

176
00:11:11,775 --> 00:11:15,433
Such field will of course prevent
the penetration of ions from outside

177
00:11:15,776 --> 00:11:19,069
as it prevents the escape

178
00:11:20,086 --> 00:11:21,637
of ions from inside.

179
00:11:21,779 --> 00:11:25,745
So here's the idea: we can use
neutral particles at high energy

180
00:11:25,745 --> 00:11:26,711
to get into the plasma,

181
00:11:26,711 --> 00:11:29,183
because neutral particles of course
don't feel the influence

182
00:11:29,183 --> 00:11:31,793
of the magnetic field
that provides confinement.

183
00:11:32,626 --> 00:11:36,017
And then let them be ionized
by the plasma itself.

184
00:11:36,017 --> 00:11:38,423
So once they are in the plasma,
they progressively become

185
00:11:38,423 --> 00:11:41,071
a beam of energetic ions,
which then, in turn,

186
00:11:41,071 --> 00:11:45,824
can transfer, by Coulomb collisions,
their energy to the plasma,

187
00:11:46,354 --> 00:11:47,765
ions and electrons.

188
00:11:47,987 --> 00:11:50,142
That's the idea of the neutral beam.

189
00:11:50,433 --> 00:11:52,290
What are the main components
in a neutral beam?

190
00:11:52,290 --> 00:11:57,135
In order to illustrate them I've taken
a very simplified, of course, layout

191
00:11:57,435 --> 00:12:00,635
of the neutral beam injector
that we use on the JET tokamak.

192
00:12:02,189 --> 00:12:05,158
Let's run through
the different elements here.

193
00:12:05,462 --> 00:12:07,353
We have, of course, a source of gas

194
00:12:07,353 --> 00:12:11,569
that's injected into the source
of ions for the beam,

195
00:12:11,569 --> 00:12:14,625
in this example,
and in the injector in the JET,

196
00:12:14,625 --> 00:12:20,217
the ions are positive ions
that are created by an arc discharge.

197
00:12:21,095 --> 00:12:23,120
There are other options, in fact.

198
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:25,915
For example, one can use rf waves

199
00:12:26,200 --> 00:12:29,235
to create the plasma

200
00:12:29,235 --> 00:12:32,550
from which we extract
the ions for the injector.

201
00:12:33,642 --> 00:12:35,957
We'll discuss that option
a little bit later.

202
00:12:36,357 --> 00:12:38,942
Then once we have a source of ions,

203
00:12:38,942 --> 00:12:42,723
we need to extract
the ions and accelerate them.

204
00:12:42,723 --> 00:12:46,105
But it's actually relatively easy
to accelerate ions,

205
00:12:47,202 --> 00:12:50,523
or charged particles in general,
because they can be accelerated

206
00:12:50,523 --> 00:12:53,728
by a set of electrostatic grids

207
00:12:54,329 --> 00:12:57,405
that provide them with the energy

208
00:12:57,405 --> 00:13:00,553
corresponding to the potential difference
that we apply to the grids.

209
00:13:01,940 --> 00:13:06,819
So now we have a beam of ions
that are highly energetic.

210
00:13:07,454 --> 00:13:10,230
What we need to do is to neutralize them

211
00:13:10,230 --> 00:13:12,383
before they are injected
into the tokamak system.

212
00:13:12,383 --> 00:13:17,235
As we said, the ions will not be able
to penetrate into the tokamak volume

213
00:13:17,235 --> 00:13:20,967
if they are still ions,
that is if they are still charged.

214
00:13:21,470 --> 00:13:23,908
So we need a chamber
that neutralizes them.

215
00:13:24,261 --> 00:13:28,351
We can inject a gas to do that,

216
00:13:28,351 --> 00:13:31,800
and attach an electron
onto the ions, in this case,

217
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:34,289
because we were starting
with positive ions.

218
00:13:35,344 --> 00:13:37,405
Of course this process
will not be 100% efficient,

219
00:13:37,405 --> 00:13:40,591
so what we need to do is to get rid of
the ions that remain ions,

220
00:13:40,591 --> 00:13:42,394
by deflecting them using a magnet

221
00:13:42,394 --> 00:13:44,661
and by collecting them on an ion dump,

222
00:13:44,661 --> 00:13:47,006
which will need to be,
of course, actively cooled,

223
00:13:48,164 --> 00:13:52,047
and then in the presence
of a very high vacuum,

224
00:13:52,047 --> 00:13:56,217
pass this beam of particles
that are still energetic,

225
00:13:56,217 --> 00:13:58,203
because they were accelerated
once they were ions,

226
00:13:58,203 --> 00:14:00,166
but they are now neutral,

227
00:14:00,564 --> 00:14:03,121
to, finally, the plasma.

228
00:14:03,694 --> 00:14:07,934
We focus now on what happens
in the plasma

229
00:14:08,404 --> 00:14:12,244
once the neutral particles
at high energy are injected into it.

230
00:14:13,124 --> 00:14:15,532
So we focus on the processes that occur

231
00:14:16,124 --> 00:14:19,145
as the beam arrives into the plasma.

232
00:14:19,145 --> 00:14:22,202
We have, essentially,
three possible processes.

233
00:14:22,202 --> 00:14:25,105
First, we can have ionization by ions.

234
00:14:27,834 --> 00:14:30,817
I take the example of a hydrogen beam,

235
00:14:30,817 --> 00:14:33,036
so the notation is a little simpler.

236
00:14:33,036 --> 00:14:34,469
So I have the beam,

237
00:14:35,071 --> 00:14:38,458
hydrogen particle, that's a neutral,

238
00:14:38,897 --> 00:14:43,903
which encounters an ion,
a positive ion in the plasma,

239
00:14:43,903 --> 00:14:45,537
and gets ionized.

240
00:14:45,537 --> 00:14:48,150
So of course there will be the creation

241
00:14:48,150 --> 00:14:51,570
of a positive ion in the beam,

242
00:14:51,570 --> 00:14:53,354
